nstitution_blurb":"Funded Talcott Hall women's dormitory (1887)."}],"research_sources":[],"research_tags":[],"artworks":[],"documents":[],"quotes":[],"statues":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Wheelbarrow of underwear at eighteen, millionaire by thirty","body":"In 1854, eighteen-year-old James Talcott arrived in New York City pushing a wheelbarrow of undergarment samples for his brother's knitting mill. By the end of the Civil War — just eleven years later — he was a millionaire, having built a factoring house whose business grew sixteen-fold in four years of wartime demand."},{"number":2,"category":"character","header":"1907 Panic: silk top hat on Wall Street","body":"When the Panic of 1907 struck, the 72-year-old James arrived on Wall Street in his long-outmoded silk top hat and frock coat, carrying a list of securities and a pencil. When the market recovered, his fortunes were greatly increased — he had never speculated in his life, so he had capital ready when others were ruined."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"Bailed Republicans from Tammany jails every Election Day","body":"An ardent Republican since the birth of the party, James took every Election Day off. After voting, he went jail to jail across New York, bailing out any Republicans who had been locked up by corrupt Tammany Hall forces after being challenged at the polls."},{"number":4,"category":"legacy","header":"Tithed ten percent of his income, every year","body":"Throughout his career James gave at least ten percent of his income to charity. He funded Talcott Hall at Oberlin College (1887), an arboretum at Mount Holyoke, a library in West Hartford, and a hospital in China. With Dwight L."},{"number":5,"category":"legacy","header":"Died at Lake Mohonk's peace community in 1916","body":"James was a frequent speaker at the Lake Mohonk Conferences on International Arbitration, the peace and Native rights gatherings convened by the Smiley brothers from 1883 onward. He died at Lake Mohonk Mountain House on August 21, 1916, age eighty-one, in the community where he had spoken on peace for decades."}],"bio":{"display_name":"James Talcott","first_name":"James","last_name":"Talcott","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1777579998/850_James_Talcott_ipbmgm.jpg","photo_notes":"Portrait. Cloudinary."},"military_service":[],"slug":"james-talcott-1835"},"U00038":{"id":"U00038","visible_default":false,"in_talcott_book":true,"classification":{"is_spouse_of_talcott_descendant":true,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1842,"month":6,"day":23,"state":"New York","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1921,"month":12,"day":14,"city":"New York City","county":"New York","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"parents":{"father_id":"X01822","mother_id":"X02417","father_research_notes":"Rev. Amzi Francis (X01822). Henrietta is from his second marriage to Mary S. Hedges (X02417); Amzi's first marriage was to Eliza Talcott (H01787, d. 1829) — Henrietta is the half-sibling of Roger A Francis (H03189) and Samuel Talcott Francis (H03190)."},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"H03207","children_ids":["T01463","T01464","T01465","T01466","T01467"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1860,"date_month":10,"date_day":31,"location_state":"New York","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1916}],"sources":[{"short":"Talcott 1876","page":"Entry 1410"}],"gender":"female","tags":["social_reform","womens_rights","educator"],"number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["charity","social_reform","education"],"notable_blurb":"YWCA founder; Barnard original trustee","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henrietta_E._Francis_Talcott","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"cross_connections":[],"baptism":{},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM025","plot_notes":"Cedar Hill Cemetery Hartford CT. FindAGrave confirms."},"residence":{"city":"New York City","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"is_placeholder":false,"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"legacy","header":"Built a Bible Society building to honor","body":"After James's death in 1916, Henrietta donated $250,000 to the New York Bible Society for a Gothic-style building in his memory — the work of architect Wilfred E. Anthony. Henrietta died in December 1921, aged 79."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"Founded Barnard with Laura Spelman Rockefeller in 1889","body":"She was one of eleven women who launched Barnard College, the women's sister to Columbia, in 1889. Her fellow founding trustees included Laura Spelman Rockefeller and suffragist Annie Nathan Meyer, and she remained a Barnard trustee for thirty-two years until her death in 1921."}],"research_tags":[],"artworks":[],"documents":[],"quotes":[],"statues":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"landmarks":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST077","institution_blurb":"Bequeathed $20,000 to Oberlin in her will; husband James funded Talcott Hall women's dormitory in 1887.","relationship":"donor"},{"institution_id":"INST110","relationship":"founder","years":"1889-1921","institution_blurb":"One of eleven charter female trustees who launched the school in 1889; endowed a $100,000 chair in Bible study and served thirty-two years on the board."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Henrietta E Francis Talcott","first_name":"Henrietta","last_name":"Talcott","married_names":["Talcott"],"middle_name":"E","maiden_name":"Francis","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1777579864/Henrietta_Talcott_bir9r8.jpg","photo_notes":"Portrait. Cloudinary."},"research_sources":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"henrietta-francis-1842"},"H01789":{"id":"H01789","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"is_talcott_descen